ce:section.ce:para:
In the past 15 years or so, more efforts have been made to develop GNPs with NIR absorption characteristics for cancer theranostics. For example, GNRs (λ
                        ab = 800 nm) were conjugated to anti- EGFR mAbs using an electrostatic physisorption approach (Huang et al., 2006). The as-synthesized conjugate was incubated in two malignant cell lines (HOC 313 clone 8 and HSC 3; HSC = human oral squamous cell carcinoma) and one non-malignant epithelial cell line (HaCaT; human keratinocytes). Subsequently, the conjugate-treated cells were used for dual molecular imaging, dark-field microscopy and selective PTT, with an NIR continuous-wave laser. As expected, the GNR–Ab conjugate had specific affinity for malignant cells relative to normal cells. The GNRs caused strong scattering of red light in the dark field, thereby producing distinct visualization and PTT of the malignant cells. Thus, the study demonstrated the simultaneous diagnosis and treatment of malignant cells using GNR–Ab conjugates in in vitro conditions. GNPs can substantially enhance the vibrational spectral intensity of Raman reporter molecules upon surface immobilization. This approach is known as SERS and is highly beneficial for the high sensitivity, multiplexed detection of target analytes. SERS nanotags, along with the conjugation of target-specific Abs, could provide a means for the non-invasive imaging and targeting of cancer cells in both in vitro and in vivo conditions. To test that hypothesis, GNPs were chemisorbed with five triphenylmethine-based reporter molecules (B2, B7, C3, C7, and C9) using a lipoic acid linker (Maiti et al., 2010). Among the tested Raman molecules, B2LA exhibited the highest SERS signal intensity and stability (>1 month) as a function of time and relative to the conventional Raman reporter malachite green isothiocyanate. Furthermore, SERS nanotags with co-immobilized B2LA and an anti-EGFR Ab generated stronger SERS signals in HER2- (SKBR3) and EGFR-positive cells (SCC-15) than in the respective negative control cells (MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231) (Fig. 6
                        ) (Maiti et al., 2010). For an in vivo proof of concept, SERS measurements were performed in Balb/c nude mice subcutaneously injected with nanotag-internalized SKBR3 cells. The in vivo Raman spectrum of the cell suspension containing the Ab-conjugated SERS nanotag was similar to that of the pristine nanotag spectrum, demonstrating its high sensitivity and selectivity. Likewise, cetuximab (CET)-conjugated PEGylated GNRs (CET-PGNRs) were analyzed as potential targeted cancer theranostics (Choi et al., 2012). The CET-PGNRs (7.75 μg Au·mL−1) showed substantial biocompatibility, with 10-times reduced cytotoxicity against EGFR positive (A-431) and EGFR negative (MCF-7) cells compared with pristine GNRs. Inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy data showed that the CET-PGNRs had 23-fold enhanced affinity toward A-431 cells relative to MCF-7 cells. The CET-PGNRs also showed targeted PTT of A-431 cells over 10 min of NIR laser irradiation (λ = 808 nm, 2.45 W cm−2). In vivo targeting studies conducted on epithelial cancer xenograft mice (EGFR overexpressed) showed strong NIR absorption of the CET-PGNRs (54 μg Au·100 μL−1) in the tumor region for 6 h. Furthermore, in in vivo PTT studies (λ = 808 nm, 2.45 W cm−2, 20 min duration) in EGFR-overexpressed A-431 xenograft mice, the CET-PGNRs caused severe toxicity to the target tumor tissue in the form of extensive pyknosis and cell vacuolization (Choi et al., 2012). Overall, those authors showed the selective cancer theranostic potential of CET-PGNRs both in vitro and in vivo. In a similar study, Kao et al. (2013) studied the cancer theranostic efficacy of 131I-labeled cetuximab (C225)-conjugated GNPs (131I–C225-GNP-PEG) against EGFR-expressing A549 human lung cancer cells. Confocal laser scanning microscopy (CLSM) observations showcased the specific uptake of C225–AuNP-PEG in A549 cells. Non-radioactive GNPs (GNP-PEG and C225-GNP-PEG) had satisfactory biocompatibility toward both malignant and normal cells (up to 0.625 μg mL−1). On the other hand, 131I–C225-GNP-PEG (0–0.625 μg mL−1 of GNPs; 0–185 kBq·mL−1 of 131I) exhibited dose-dependent cytotoxicity, with A549 cell viability reduced to about 37%. In vivo studies performed in a A549 xenograft mouse model showed clear tumor uptake 4 h post injection. The study further supported the potential of GNP–Ab conjugates as a potent, non-invasive tool for the simultaneous imaging and treatment of cancer cells (Kao et al., 2013). Other researchers also used GNP–Ab conjugates to target EGFR-overexpressing cancer cells (Conde et al., 2014; Karmani et al., 2013).
